    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-10-08T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-10-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="1237"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1237">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">751G.00/10–354</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Conversation, by the Secretary of State</hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d1237fn1">This memorandum of conversation was transmitted to
                        Saigon in telegram 1389 of Oct. 4 (also sent to Paris as telegram
                        1235).(751G.00/10–454)</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" type="conversation-or-meeting-date"
                            when="1954-10-08">October 8, 1954</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="center">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Memorandum Of Conversation With <persName corresp="#p_MFP1"
                            >Mendes-France</persName>
                    </hi>
                </p>
                <list type="references">
                    <head>Re:</head>
                    <item>Indochina</item>
                </list>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_MFP1">Mendes-France</persName> said that he agreed that we
                    should back <persName corresp="#p_NDD1">Diem</persName> as Premier. However, he
                    doubted that he had the necessary qualities. <persName corresp="#p_MFP1"
                        >Mendes-France</persName> admitted however that he saw no one else who did
                    have those qualities. He said he realized that <persName corresp="#p_NDD1"
                        >Diem</persName> was somewhat anti-French. He did not blame him for this and
                    recognized that any successful leader in Vietnam would have to be somewhat
                    anti-French. What worried him was not this quality, but the apparent lack of
                    administrative qualities and ability to get along with others. He would however
                    give <persName corresp="#p_NDD1">Diem</persName> a good try.</p>
                <p>He referred to <persName corresp="#p_BD1">Bao Dai</persName>. I mentioned that
                        <persName corresp="#p_HDR1">Heath</persName> was on his way to see <persName
                        corresp="#p_BD1">Bao Dai</persName> with a view to getting him also to
                    support <persName corresp="#p_NDD1">Diem</persName>. <persName corresp="#p_MFP1"
                        >Mendes-France</persName> said he felt that <persName corresp="#p_BD1">Bao
                        Dai</persName> was about played out and had little more influence on the
                    situation. He said that <persName corresp="#p_BD1">Bao Dai</persName> could be
                    very largely ignored, except that he was useful from the standpoint of giving
                    “legitimacy” to the Government of Vietnam.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">John Foster Dulles</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
